        </aside>

        <article class="article-content">
          <div class="article-intro">
            <p class="lead">Hastings Highlands is one of the last truly unregulated cottage country markets in Ontario. No license. No principal residence rule. No night limit. No Municipal Accommodation Tax. If you own a cottage on Baptiste Lake, a cabin near Maynooth, or an investment property in Bancroft, the municipality is not standing in your way.</p>
            <p class="lead">That puts Hastings Highlands in a rare position. While neighbouring cottage regions like <a href="/blog/muskoka-lakes-airbnb-short-term-rental-rules-2026">Muskoka Lakes</a> now charge $1,000 per year for a license and <a href="/blog/huntsville-airbnb-short-term-rental-rules-2026">Huntsville</a> requires 12 months of ownership before you can even apply, Hastings Highlands lets you list your property the day you get the keys. Here's the complete breakdown of what you need to know.</p>
          </div>

          <h2 id="current-rules">Current Rules: The Quick Summary</h2>
          <p>Here's what every Hastings Highlands property owner wants to know:</p>

          <div class="comparison-table">
            <div class="comparison-header">
              <div class="comparison-col">Requirement</div>
              <div class="comparison-col highlight">Hastings Highlands (2026)</div>
            </div>
            <div class="comparison-row">
              <div class="comparison-col">STR license required?</div>
              <div class="comparison-col highlight"><strong>No</strong></div>
            </div>
            <div class="comparison-row">
              <div class="comparison-col">Principal residence required?</div>
              <div class="comparison-col highlight"><strong>No</strong></div>
            </div>
            <div class="comparison-row">
              <div class="comparison-col">Annual night limit?</div>
              <div class="comparison-col highlight"><strong>None</strong></div>
            </div>
            <div class="comparison-row">
              <div class="comparison-col">Municipal Accommodation Tax?</div>
              <div class="comparison-col highlight"><strong>None</strong></div>
            </div>
            <div class="comparison-row">
              <div class="comparison-col">Registration number on listing?</div>
              <div class="comparison-col highlight"><strong>Not required</strong></div>
            </div>
            <div class="comparison-row">
              <div class="comparison-col">Investment properties allowed?</div>
              <div class="comparison-col highlight"><strong>Yes</strong></div>
            </div>
            <div class="comparison-row">
              <div class="comparison-col">Cottages allowed?</div>
              <div class="comparison-col highlight"><strong>Yes</strong></div>
            </div>
          </div>

          <p>Hastings Highlands has not enacted any STR specific bylaws. You can review the full list of <a href="https://www.hastingshighlands.ca/municipal-services/bylaws-and-policies/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Hastings Highlands bylaws here</a>. General municipal bylaws for noise, property standards, and fire safety still apply (more on that below), but there is no licensing framework, no registration process, and no accommodation tax.</p>

          <h2 id="no-license">No License or Registration Required</h2>
          <p>Unlike Muskoka Lakes, Huntsville, Kawartha Lakes, and Minden Hills, which have all rolled out STR licensing programs, Hastings Highlands has not introduced any licensing requirement for short-term rental operators.</p>

          <p>This means:</p>
          <ul>
            <li><strong>No application to file</strong> with the Municipality</li>
            <li><strong>No fees to pay</strong> for a permit or license</li>
            <li><strong>No registration number</strong> to display on your listing</li>
            <li><strong>No annual renewal</strong> process</li>
            <li><strong>No property inspection</strong> required by the municipality</li>
            <li><strong>No fire inspection</strong> mandated before listing</li>
          </ul>

          <p>The municipality's <a href="https://www.hastingshighlands.ca/municipal-services/bylaw-enforcement/business-licenses/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Business Licensing By-law 2024-005</a> only covers vendors, mobile food trucks, seasonal markets, and door-to-door sales. Short-term rentals are not mentioned at all. Compare that to Muskoka Lakes, where hosts pay $1,000 per year, need a septic compliance letter, and face a demerit point system that can revoke their license.</p>

          <h2 id="no-principal-residence">No Principal Residence Requirement</h2>
          <p>This is where Hastings Highlands really shines for cottage investors. Most regulated Ontario municipalities require the property to be your principal residence, the home where you actually live. That rule kills investment property and cottage Airbnbs.</p>

          <p>Hastings Highlands has no such restriction. You can operate short-term rentals on:</p>
          <ul>
            <li><strong>A seasonal cottage</strong> you use a few weeks per year</li>
            <li><strong>An investment property</strong> purchased specifically for rental income</li>
            <li><strong>Your primary home</strong> (whole unit or individual rooms)</li>
            <li><strong>Multiple properties</strong> (no limit on how many STRs you can run)</li>
          </ul>

          <div class="callout">
            <div class="callout-icon">
              <svg width="24" height="24" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2">
                <circle cx="12" cy="12" r="10"></circle>
                <path d="M12 16v-4"></path>
                <path d="M12 8h.01"></path>
              </svg>
            </div>
            <div class="callout-content">
              <strong>Why this matters for cottage owners:</strong> Hastings Highlands has 3,529 total dwellings but only 2,007 are occupied year-round. That means about 43% of homes are seasonal or vacant, according to <a href="https://www12.statcan.gc.ca/census-recensement/2021/dp-pd/prof/details/page.cfm?Lang=E&SearchText=hastings+highlands&DGUIDlist=2021A00053512027" target="_blank" rel="noopener">census data</a>. Many of those are cottages that sit empty most of the year. In Hastings Highlands, you can rent them out with zero regulatory barriers. In Huntsville or Muskoka Lakes, you'd need a license, inspections, and potentially couldn't qualify at all.
            </div>
          </div>

          <h2 id="no-night-limit">No Night Limit</h2>
          <p>Many Ontario municipalities cap how many nights per year you can rent your entire home. Hastings Highlands has no such cap.</p>

          <p>You can rent your property 365 nights a year. There is no limit on entire-home or partial-home rentals. For cottage owners who only use their property a few summer weekends, this means you can rent it out the other 48+ weeks of the year without any municipal restriction.</p>

          <h2 id="no-mat">No Municipal Accommodation Tax</h2>
          <p>Hastings Highlands does not charge MAT (Municipal Accommodation Tax) on short-term rentals. Here's what your cottage country neighbours charge:</p>

          <div class="comparison-table">
            <div class="comparison-header">
              <div class="comparison-col">Municipality</div>
              <div class="comparison-col highlight">MAT Rate</div>
            </div>
            <div class="comparison-row">
              <div class="comparison-col">Toronto</div>
              <div class="comparison-col highlight"><strong>8.5%</strong></div>
            </div>
            <div class="comparison-row">
              <div class="comparison-col">Oshawa</div>
              <div class="comparison-col highlight"><strong>5%</strong></div>
            </div>
            <div class="comparison-row">
              <div class="comparison-col">Huntsville</div>
              <div class="comparison-col highlight"><strong>Yes (rate varies)</strong></div>
            </div>
            <div class="comparison-row">
              <div class="comparison-col">St. Catharines</div>
              <div class="comparison-col highlight"><strong>4%</strong></div>
            </div>
            <div class="comparison-row">
              <div class="comparison-col highlight-green">Hastings Highlands</div>
              <div class="comparison-col highlight"><strong>0%</strong></div>
            </div>
          </div>

          <p>On a $200/night cottage booking with 4% MAT, your guest would pay an extra $8 per night. Over a busy summer with 60 nights booked, that's $480 in tax that either eats into your revenue or makes your listing less competitive on price. In Hastings Highlands, it's zero.</p>

          <h2 id="why-unregulated">Why Hastings Highlands Is Still Unregulated</h2>
          <p>This isn't just a case of a small municipality not getting around to it. The broader Hastings County region has actively considered and rejected STR regulation.</p>

          <p>In April 2024, neighbouring Centre Hastings conducted a community survey about short-term rentals. The results were clear: <strong>61% of residents said short-term rentals were not disrupting their lives</strong>. Council chose not to regulate. <a href="https://www.quintenews.com/2024/04/18/329590/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Quinte News reported the decision</a>, which reflects the broader sentiment across Hastings County.</p>

          <p>Several factors explain why Hastings Highlands hasn't followed the Muskoka trend:</p>
          <ul>
            <li><strong>Low density population:</strong> With only 4,385 permanent residents spread across a huge rural municipality, the "neighbourhood disruption" complaints that drive regulation in urban areas simply don't exist at the same scale.</li>
            <li><strong>Cottage economy:</strong> About 43% of dwellings are seasonal or vacant. Tourism and cottage rentals are an economic lifeline, not a nuisance. The municipality benefits from visitors spending money at local businesses.</li>
            <li><strong>No housing crisis:</strong> Unlike Toronto or Muskoka's popular towns, Hastings Highlands doesn't have the same rental housing shortage that motivates principal residence rules.</li>
            <li><strong>Zoning grey area:</strong> The <a href="https://www.hastingshighlands.ca/business-development/planning-and-development/zoning/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Zoning By-law 2004-035</a> (consolidated 2023) predates the Airbnb era entirely. It defines tourist commercial and rural zones but doesn't specifically address short-term rentals, leaving them in a grey area that the municipality has chosen not to close.</li>
          </ul>

          <p>The <a href="https://ocrma.ca/str-bylaws/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Ontario Cottage Rental Managers Association (OCRMA)</a> tracks STR bylaws across Ontario, and Hastings Highlands is not listed as having any regulations. The neighbouring Township of Tudor and Cashel even maintains an <a href="https://tudorandcashel.com/services/short-term-rental-information/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">STR information page</a> confirming there are no local STR bylaws in their jurisdiction either.</p>

          <div class="callout">
            <div class="callout-icon">
              <svg width="24" height="24" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2">
                <circle cx="12" cy="12" r="10"></circle>
                <path d="M12 16v-4"></path>
                <path d="M12 8h.01"></path>
              </svg>
            </div>
            <div class="callout-content">
              <strong>Worth watching:</strong> Surrounding cottage areas are moving toward regulation. Muskoka Lakes introduced a $1,000/year license in 2025. Kawartha Lakes requires licensing. Haliburton County is developing a regional bylaw. Minden Hills is already licensed. If a provincial framework ever gets proposed, Hastings Highlands could be affected. For now, the window is wide open.
            </div>
          </div>

          <h2 id="market-data">Hastings Highlands Airbnb Market Data</h2>
          <p>Here's what the numbers look like for short-term rentals in Hastings Highlands and the Bancroft area:</p>

          <div class="comparison-table">
            <div class="comparison-header">
              <div class="comparison-col">Metric</div>
