              <div class="comparison-col highlight"><strong>CA$49,221</strong> (Airbtics)</div>
            </div>
            <div class="comparison-row">
              <div class="comparison-col">Median annual revenue (Bancroft)</div>
              <div class="comparison-col highlight"><strong>$29,946</strong> (AirROI)</div>
            </div>
            <div class="comparison-row">
              <div class="comparison-col">Top 10% earn</div>
              <div class="comparison-col highlight"><strong>$7,193+/month</strong> ($86K+/year)</div>
            </div>
            <div class="comparison-row">
              <div class="comparison-col">Average daily rate (Bancroft)</div>
              <div class="comparison-col highlight"><strong>$216</strong></div>
            </div>
            <div class="comparison-row">
              <div class="comparison-col">Average occupancy</div>
              <div class="comparison-col highlight"><strong>43.9% (Bancroft) / 54% (Highlands)</strong></div>
            </div>
            <div class="comparison-row">
              <div class="comparison-col">Year-over-year revenue growth</div>
              <div class="comparison-col highlight"><strong>66.4%</strong></div>
            </div>
            <div class="comparison-row">
              <div class="comparison-col">Peak months (Jul/Aug)</div>
              <div class="comparison-col highlight"><strong>58.6% occ, $219 ADR</strong></div>
            </div>
            <div class="comparison-row">
              <div class="comparison-col">Entire home listings</div>
              <div class="comparison-col highlight"><strong>90.5%</strong></div>
            </div>
            <div class="comparison-row">
              <div class="comparison-col">Houses/cottages</div>
              <div class="comparison-col highlight"><strong>66.7%</strong></div>
            </div>
            <div class="comparison-row">
              <div class="comparison-col">Guest origin</div>
              <div class="comparison-col highlight"><strong>88.9% domestic (mostly Toronto)</strong></div>
            </div>
            <div class="comparison-row">
              <div class="comparison-col">Avg booking lead time</div>
              <div class="comparison-col highlight"><strong>57 days (86 summer, 32 winter)</strong></div>
            </div>
          </div>

          <p>Sources: <a href="https://www.airroi.com/report/world/canada/ontario/bancroft" target="_blank" rel="noopener">AirROI Bancroft</a> and <a href="https://airbtics.com/annual-airbnb-revenue-in-hastings-highlands-ontario-canada" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Airbtics Hastings Highlands</a>.</p>

          <p>That 66.4% year-over-year revenue growth is remarkable. It signals a market that's still growing, not saturated. The top 10% of hosts are pulling in over $86,000 per year. Even the median earner in the Bancroft area is making nearly $30,000 annually, which is solid for a seasonal cottage market with zero regulatory costs. No license fee. No MAT eating into your revenue. No night cap cutting your season short.</p>

          <p>The 57 day average booking lead time is especially useful for pricing strategy. Summer guests book 86 days out, nearly three months ahead. If your summer calendar isn't priced and published by April, you're already leaving money on the table.</p>

          <h2 id="what-does-apply">What Rules DO Apply in Hastings Highlands</h2>
          <p>No STR bylaw doesn't mean anything goes. Hastings Highlands' general municipal bylaws apply to every property, and they'll definitely apply if guests cause problems:</p>

          <h3>Noise Bylaw (By-law 2020-062)</h3>
          <p>Hastings Highlands enforces noise restrictions under <strong>By-law 2020-062</strong>. Loud parties, late night bonfires, and disruptive guests can result in complaints and fines. This is cottage country, so your neighbours may be seasonal residents who came for peace and quiet. Set clear quiet hours in your house rules, especially for lakefront properties where sound carries over water. You can review all bylaws on the <a href="https://www.hastingshighlands.ca/municipal-services/bylaws-and-policies/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">municipality's bylaws page</a>.</p>

          <h3>Property Standards</h3>
          <p>Your property must meet the municipality's property standards bylaw. This covers exterior maintenance, structural safety, and general upkeep. A poorly maintained rental can trigger neighbour complaints and municipal inspections regardless of whether STR bylaws exist.</p>

          <h3>Open Air Burning</h3>
          <p>Hastings Highlands has specific bylaws around open air burning. Campfires are a big part of cottage life, but you need to follow the rules for fire permits, burn bans, and safe distances. Make sure your listing notes the fire rules and provide guests with clear instructions. Summer burn bans are common during dry periods.</p>

          <h3>Fire Code and Building Code</h3>
          <p>Ontario's Fire Protection and Prevention Act applies to every dwelling. Smoke detectors, carbon monoxide detectors, and proper egress from bedrooms are required. This is especially important for older cottages that may not have been updated to current code. Check your CO detectors, especially if your cottage has a wood stove or propane appliances.</p>

          <h3>Zoning</h3>
          <p>The <a href="https://www.hastingshighlands.ca/business-development/planning-and-development/zoning/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Zoning By-law 2004-035</a> (consolidated 2023) does not specifically define short-term rentals. It predates the modern Airbnb era. The bylaw references tourist commercial zones and rural residential zones, but typical cottage rentals operate in a grey area. The municipality has not taken enforcement action against standard STR operations.</p>

          <div class="warning-box">
            <h4>Septic Systems Matter</h4>
            <p>Many Hastings Highlands properties rely on septic systems rather than municipal sewers. Overloading a septic system with too many guests can cause failures that are expensive to fix and harmful to the lake. Know your system's capacity and set your maximum occupancy accordingly. This isn't a bylaw requirement for STRs, but it's a practical reality of cottage hosting.</p>
          </div>

          <h2 id="comparison">Hastings Highlands vs Cottage Country Neighbours</h2>
          <p>Here's how Hastings Highlands compares to other popular cottage country municipalities:</p>

